  "prompt": "What's the difference between shares and stocks?",
  "response": "The terms \"shares\" and \"stocks\" are often used interchangeably, but they can have different meanings depending on the context.\n\n1. **Stocks**: This is a general term that refers to the ownership certificates of any company. When you own stocks, you essentially own a part of one or more companies. Stocks can be either common or preferred, and they represent a claim on a company's assets and earnings.\n\n2. **Shares**: This term usually refers to the specific units of stock that you can own in a particular company. When you purchase \"shares,\" you are buying a certain number of units of a single company's stock. For example, if you own 100 shares of Company A, you have 100 units of ownership in that company.\n\nIn summary, \"stock\" refers to the overall market or collection of ownership in various companies, while \"shares\" refer to the specific units of ownership in a particular company.",
